1. Python 2 vs Python 3
Python 3 is a complete redesign focused on consistency and Unicode support. The biggest difference is string handling—Python 2 treats strings as ASCII by default, while Python 3 uses Unicode (str) by default, which avoids encoding issues in global applications. Division behavior also changed (5/2 = 2 in Py2 vs 2.5 in Py3). Python 3 improved libraries, removed redundancy, and introduced features like async/await. Python 2 is now end-of-life, so all modern development uses Python 3. In interviews, emphasize performance improvements, better memory handling, and ecosystem support.
________________________________________
2. Python Memory Management
Python uses automatic memory management with a combination of:
•	Reference counting
•	Garbage Collector (GC)
Every object keeps a reference count; when it reaches zero, memory is freed immediately. However, reference counting cannot handle circular references, so Python uses a cyclic garbage collector to detect and clean them. Memory is managed in private heaps, and the Python memory manager allocates space efficiently. Interview tip: mention pymalloc allocator, which optimizes small object allocations. Also highlight tools like gc module and tracemalloc for debugging memory issues.
________________________________________
3. Global Interpreter Lock (GIL)
The GIL is a mutex that ensures only one thread executes Python bytecode at a time. It simplifies memory management and avoids race conditions in CPython. However, it becomes a bottleneck for CPU-bound multithreading, limiting parallel execution. For I/O-bound tasks, threads still work well because GIL is released during I/O operations. To bypass GIL for CPU-heavy tasks, use:
•	multiprocessing
•	C extensions
•	NumPy (internally optimized)
In interviews, clearly state:
👉 “GIL affects CPU-bound concurrency but not I/O-bound workloads significantly.”
