4. Deep Copy vs Shallow Copy
A shallow copy creates a new object but references the same nested objects. A deep copy creates a completely independent copy, including all nested objects.
Example:
•	Shallow → changes inside nested objects affect both copies
•	Deep → completely isolated
Use:
•	copy.copy() → shallow
•	copy.deepcopy() → deep
Interview angle:
Shallow copy is faster and memory-efficient but risky with mutable objects. Deep copy is safer but expensive. Understanding this is critical when dealing with complex data structures or caching systems.
