5. Mutable vs Immutable Objects
Mutable objects can be changed after creation (list, dict, set).
Immutable objects cannot be changed (int, string, tuple).
Example:
x = [1, 2]
x.append(3)  # mutable

y = "hello"
y = y + " world"  # new object created
Why important:
•	Immutable objects are thread-safe
•	Used as dictionary keys (e.g., tuples)
Interview insight:
Python uses immutability for performance optimization and caching (interning). Also affects how variables behave when passed to functions.
