21. Threading vs Multiprocessing vs Asyncio
These are three ways to achieve concurrency in Python:
•	Threading: Uses multiple threads within a process. Limited by the GIL, so not ideal for CPU-bound tasks but good for I/O-bound tasks (e.g., API calls).
•	Multiprocessing: Uses separate processes with independent memory. Bypasses GIL, ideal for CPU-intensive tasks.
•	Asyncio: Uses a single-threaded event loop with coroutines. Best for high-performance I/O operations like handling thousands of network requests.
Interview tip:
👉 Use threading for lightweight I/O, multiprocessing for CPU-heavy tasks, asyncio for scalable async systems.
________________________________________
22. Parallel Processing with Multiprocessing
Multiprocessing creates separate processes, each with its own Python interpreter and memory space. This avoids the GIL, allowing true parallel execution on multiple CPU cores.
Example use cases:
•	Data processing
•	Image/video processing
•	Machine learning workloads
Python provides multiprocessing.Pool for easy parallel execution.
Interview insight:
Although powerful, multiprocessing has overhead due to inter-process communication (IPC) and memory duplication, so it should be used carefully.
________________________________________
23. Async/Await in Python
async/await is used to write asynchronous code in a clean, readable way. It is built on top of coroutines and the event loop.
Example:
async def fetch():
    return "data"
Key idea:
•	async defines coroutine
•	await pauses execution until result is ready
Used in frameworks like FastAPI and aiohttp.
Interview insight:
Async improves throughput, not raw execution speed, making it ideal for I/O-heavy applications like APIs.
